docs/architecture/v1-coordination-implementation-plan.md:600:These integration tests are **not** part of v1 coordination package scope. They belong in a subsequent integration phase, analogous to `core-sessions.test.ts` and `core-sessions-surfaces.test.ts` for the foundation packages.
docs/architecture/package-boundary-map.md:13:The goal is to prevent duplicate assistant-runtime work while avoiding leakage of transport infrastructure or product-specific behavior into the wrong layer.
docs/architecture/package-boundary-map.md:19:- if the capability is transport, auth, scheduling substrate, or low-level action dispatch, keep it in Relay foundation
docs/architecture/package-boundary-map.md:20:- if the capability assumes an assistant identity, memory model, session continuity model, specialist orchestration model, or focused inter-agent connectivity model, move it here
docs/architecture/package-boundary-map.md:31:- channel and transport session substrate
docs/architecture/package-boundary-map.md:36:- transport-level observability
docs/architecture/package-boundary-map.md:50:- memory scopes, retrieval, persistence contracts, promotion, compaction
docs/architecture/package-boundary-map.md:52:- assistant session continuity across surfaces
docs/architecture/package-boundary-map.md:53:- assistant-facing surface abstractions above normalized transport events
docs/architecture/package-boundary-map.md:55:- focused inter-agent connectivity, signaling, and convergence contracts
docs/architecture/package-boundary-map.md:56:- assistant-level routing, latency, depth, and budget-aware policy hooks
docs/architecture/package-boundary-map.md:101:- provider-specific transport code
docs/architecture/package-boundary-map.md:102:- memory backend implementation details
docs/architecture/package-boundary-map.md:105:### `@relay-assistant/memory`
docs/architecture/package-boundary-map.md:109:- memory scopes such as user, session, workspace, org, and object
docs/architecture/package-boundary-map.md:111:- memory adapter interfaces for future backends
docs/architecture/package-boundary-map.md:116:- one surface's thread model as the only memory key shape
docs/architecture/package-boundary-map.md:138:- attachment of multiple surfaces to one assistant session
docs/architecture/package-boundary-map.md:144:- raw transport sessions
docs/architecture/package-boundary-map.md:147:### `@relay-assistant/surfaces`
docs/architecture/package-boundary-map.md:152:- assistant-layer fanout policy describing which connected surfaces should receive a given assistant response
docs/architecture/package-boundary-map.md:157:- Relay foundation still owns actual transport delivery to each destination
