docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:98:| WF-C1 | Narrowcast attention | Specialist → emit(attention.raise, selected) → audience resolver → onSignal → coordination reads |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:99:| WF-C2 | Reviewer conflict | Specialist A → emit(conflict.active, coordinator) → onSignal → coordination queries → arbitrates → resolve() |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:100:| WF-C3 | Specialist handoff | Specialist A → emit(handoff.ready, selected) → onSignal → downstream specialist begins → coordination resolves |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:101:| WF-C4 | Blocker uncertainty routing | Specialist → emit(escalation.uncertainty, high) → routingEscalationHook → routing returns mode → onSignal → coordination adjusts |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:108:| Connectivity → routing | Import `RequestedRoutingMode` type only. Never call routing methods directly. |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:110:| Connectivity → surfaces | Forbidden. |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:111:| Connectivity → memory | Forbidden. |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:112:| Connectivity → coordination | Forbidden. Coordination depends on connectivity, not vice versa. |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:113:| Coordination → connectivity | Allowed. Coordination imports and uses `ConnectivityLayer`. |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:114:| Routing → connectivity | Allowed. Routing implements `RoutingEscalationHook`. |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:124:| Distributed / cross-process signal delivery | v1 is single-process; distribution requires transport integration | v1.2+ |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:125:| Persistent signal log | In-memory only; persistence requires storage adapter | v1.2+ |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:127:| Tenant-aware signal routing | No multi-tenant semantics in v1; cloud concern | Cloud adapter |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:134:| Queued vs immediate routing mode application | v1 applies routing hints immediately via hook; queuing deferred | Before WF-C4 hardening |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:141:- Connectivity will never own message routing decisions (routing's job)
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:142:- Connectivity will never own coordinator/specialist orchestration (coordination's job)
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:157:| Call direction | Coordination calls connectivity (`emit`, `query`, `resolve`, `onSignal`). Connectivity never calls coordination. | Coordination provides `SelectedAudienceResolver` to connectivity. |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:160:The boundary is strict: connectivity is the signaling mechanism; coordination is the decision-maker that uses signals as input. Coordination registers an `onSignal` callback to react. Coordination provides the `SelectedAudienceResolver` so connectivity can resolve `audience='selected'` without knowing the coordination topology.
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:168:| Call direction | One-directional: connectivity calls routing's `RoutingEscalationHook.onEscalation()` during escalation emit. Routing never calls connectivity. | Routing implements `RoutingEscalationHook` and registers it with connectivity at initialization. |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:169:| Example | Specialist emits `escalation.uncertainty` with `priority='high'` → connectivity calls hook | Router receives the signal, returns `'deep'` as requested mode, applies it to subsequent `decide()` calls |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:171:Connectivity does not know what routing does with the escalation. Routing does not emit signals. The interface between them is a single hook with a single method.
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:179:| Interaction in v1 | None. Signals are in-process. No transport layer involved. | Transport delivers user-facing messages via surfaces, not internal signals. |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:180:| Future interaction | When signals cross process boundaries (v1.2+), transport becomes the delivery mechanism for signals. Connectivity will define signal serialization; transport will deliver it. | Transport will gain a signal delivery adapter alongside its existing message delivery. |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:182:In v1, connectivity has zero runtime dependency on transport. Signals are function calls and callbacks within a single Node process.
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:195:| `handoff` | Downstream component can proceed; this specialist is done with its step | Planner finished a plan; reviewer completed a pass; memory enrichment is ready for synthesis |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:196:| `escalation` | Current path should change immediately; high urgency | Policy issue discovered; unsafe action path; uncertainty too high for current routing mode |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:212:| `escalation.uncertainty` | escalation | High uncertainty; requesting routing mode change |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:222:| `escalation.required` / `escalation.immediate` | Consolidated into `escalation.interrupt` (immediate) and `escalation.uncertainty` (requesting deeper routing); two classes cover the same semantic space with clearer distinction |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:229:| Priority | Effect on routing | Effect on suppression |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:231:| `low` | Informational; does not influence routing mode | May be suppressed aggressively |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:232:| `normal` | Advisory; may influence next routing decision | Standard suppression window |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:233:| `high` | May trigger immediate routing mode change via escalation hook | Suppression window shortened or bypassed |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:234:| `critical` | Must trigger routing escalation; coordinator must acknowledge | Never suppressed |
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:242:- **Interpreted** by coordination and routing, not by connectivity itself
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:244:Connectivity stores and forwards the value. It does not make decisions based on the value. This keeps the interpretation logic in coordination and routing where it belongs.
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:252:A specialist may discover that the current routing mode (`cheap` or `fast`) cannot produce an answer that meets the fixed quality bar. The system needs a way to request a deeper routing mode without connectivity making routing decisions directly.
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:260:ConnectivityLayer ──routingEscalationHook.onEscalation(signal)──► Router
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:263:Coordination ──reads signal + routing context──► adjusts specialist budget or re-delegates
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:268:1. **Specialist emits** an escalation signal via `connectivityLayer.emit()`. The signal carries `messageClass='escalation'`, a `signalClass` (`interrupt` or `uncertainty`), and a `priority`.
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:270:2. **Connectivity calls the routing hook** synchronously during `emit()`. The `RoutingEscalationHook.onEscalation(signal)` method receives the full signal. Routing decides whether to change the mode for subsequent `router.decide()` calls. It returns the requested mode or `void`.
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:272:3. **Connectivity does not store or act on the returned mode.** It is a notification, not a command. The routing layer applies it internally to its own state.
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:274:4. **Connectivity fires `onSignal` callbacks** to notify coordination and any other subscribers that the escalation was emitted.
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:276:5. **Coordination reads the escalation signal** and the current routing context to decide what action to take — re-delegate, adjust budgets, request more input, or proceed.
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:28[stderr] 0:- **Connectivity does not know about routing modes.** It imports the `RequestedRoutingMode` type for the hook interface but never evaluates or stores mode values.
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:281:- **Routing does not depend on connectivity at runtime.** Routing implements the hook interface and registers itself. If no hook is registered, escalation signals are still emitted and reach `onSignal` subscribers — routing just does not react to them automatically.
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:282:- **The quality bar is routing's responsibility.** Connectivity signals that something is wrong. Routing decides whether to change the envelope. Coordination decides whether to change the plan.
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:283:- **The hook is optional.** Systems without routing (e.g., single-model setups) can use connectivity for coordination signals without wiring a routing hook. Escalation signals still function as coordination signals.
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:287:- Connectivity does not queue routing requests. The hook is called synchronously during emit and the result is fire-and-forget from connectivity's perspective.
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:288:- Connectivity does not enforce that routing actually changes the mode. Routing may ignore the escalation if policy constraints prevent mode change.
docs/architecture/v1-connectivity-scope.md:289:- Connectivity does not escalate on behalf of coordination. Only the component that detects the problem emits the escalation. Coordination reacts to it but does not re-emit.
