docs/specs/v1-surfaces-spec.md:1:# v1 Surfaces Spec — `@relay-assistant/surfaces`
docs/specs/v1-surfaces-spec.md:5:**Package:** `@relay-assistant/surfaces`
docs/specs/v1-surfaces-spec.md:12:`@relay-assistant/surfaces` manages the connections between the assistant runtime and user-facing interaction mediums. A surface is any channel through which a user sends messages to or receives messages from the assistant (web chat, Slack, desktop, API, etc.).
docs/specs/v1-surfaces-spec.md:20:- Fanout — when a session has multiple attached surfaces, deliver an outbound event to all of them (with configurable policy)
docs/specs/v1-surfaces-spec.md:22:- Surface capability advertising — surfaces may declare what formatting capabilities they support; format hooks receive this as context
docs/specs/v1-surfaces-spec.md:25:- The underlying transport protocol (HTTP, WebSocket, Slack Events API). That is the relay foundation.
docs/specs/v1-surfaces-spec.md:27:- Routing decisions about which model to call (→ `@relay-assistant/routing`)
docs/specs/v1-surfaces-spec.md:28:- Memory (→ `@relay-assistant/memory`)
docs/specs/v1-surfaces-spec.md:37:- Surfaces does not buffer or queue messages for offline surfaces. If a surface adapter's send fails, the error propagates to the caller.
docs/specs/v1-surfaces-spec.md:39:- Surfaces is not a notification system. Proactive delivery is driven by `@relay-assistant/proactive`; surfaces handles the actual send once triggered.
docs/specs/v1-surfaces-spec.md:127: * Interface implemented by the surface-specific transport integration.
docs/specs/v1-surfaces-spec.md:129: * Surfaces package never imports a specific transport library.
