docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:46:- memory and proactive packages are justified
docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:53:- one assistant experience across multiple surfaces
docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:60:- `sessions` and `surfaces` should be first-class packages
docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:65:NightCTO contributes the strongest coordination signals:
docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:74:- `coordination`, `policy`, `memory`, and `proactive` are all justified
docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:82:- continuity across surfaces
docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:85:- focused internal connectivity
docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:92:### Sage vs NightCTO on memory
docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:94:Sage's memory signals emphasize conversation continuity, workspace context retention, and proactive follow-up evidence. NightCTO's memory signals emphasize per-client continuity, specialist context, and durable service relationships.
docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:98:- the memory layer cannot assume that every durable object is just a chat thread
docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:101:### MSD vs Sage on sessions and surfaces
docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:103:MSD's strongest contribution is shared session convergence across multiple surfaces. Sage currently shows more product-specific memory and proactive behavior, but its runtime still implies the need for consistent session continuity when the assistant appears in multiple places.
docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:106:- the session layer should treat surfaces as attachments to one assistant session rather than as the primary continuity object
docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:109:### NightCTO vs MSD on coordination
docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:114:- coordination should be separated from domain-specific specialist lineups
docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:117:### Why connectivity deserves its own package
docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:119:The internal systems do not merely need transport; they need efficient communication between sophisticated subsystems.
docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:128:That is why a distinct `@relay-assistant/connectivity` package is justified above Relay transport and alongside coordination.
docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:134:- Relay foundation for transport and substrate
docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:142:Workforce contributes the strongest routing and token-budgeting signals:
docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:147:- routing profiles that preserve quality while changing operating envelope
docs/research/internal-system-comparison.md:151:- `routing` should be a first-class assistant-sdk package
